Question 1¶

Explain the differences between RDD and a traditional Relational Database System.

  • RDD (Resilient Distributed Dataset) represents an immutable, partitioned collection of elements that can be operated on in parallel.Immutable elements means that once you create an RDD you can't change it. RDDs are fault tolerant, hence in case of failure, they recover automatically.

  • Relational Database System stores and provides access to data points that are related to one another. It's a straightforward way of representing data tables. Structured Query Language (SQL) is almost used for this type of databases. It very important to state that each row in the table is a record with a unique ID (Key), columns (attributes). *Each record usually has a value for each attribute.

Some Differences between these two:

  • Structure and Storage: We know RDD represents an immutable partitioned collected of elements (unstructured data) which are stored in memory or on disks of different machines of a cluster. In contrast, RDB stores structured data in table format with rows and columns. It (RDB) organizes data into relatable tables as stated above and stores information within disks.

  • API/Languages: RDD has API for the following languages (Python, R, Scala, and Java) which help us perform many important operations for data manipulation. In the other hand, Relational Databases use SQL to manipulate the and query data.

  • Performance/Reading Files: As we know, RDBs are more used for data retrieval tasks and reporting (analytics). Since Spark has API for different programming languages, we can even use RDDs for other tasks like data processing and machine learning. We can do more data science related tasks using RDDS than using RDBs. It is also easier to read CSV, Text, and XML Files in RDDs.

  • Fault Tolerance: RDDs are fault tolerance by nature, meaning that if something goes wrong it can recover automatically. In order to make a Relational Database Fault Tolerance, we can use the "ACID" guidelines to ensure good transactions. "ACID" stands for Atomocity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability. This will help with data integrity if something wrong happens. Professor Scrivner talked about this.

stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

p = {'I','you','my','mine','myself','we','us','our','ours','ourselves',
      'your','yours','yourself','he','him','his','himself','she','her',

In [ ]:
wrd_count = txt.flatMap(lambda line: line.split(' ')) \
             .filter(lambda word: word.lower() not in filtered_words) \
             .map(lambda word: (word, 1)) \
             .reduceByKey(lambda x, y: x + y)

output = wrd_count.collect()

for (word, count) in output:
    print(f'{word}, {count}')

3.1 Combiner Method¶

We are going to use the createCombiner(), mergeValue(), and mergeCombiner() in order to use the combineByKey() function.

Lets create the case in which we want to find the average 'Present_Tmin' for each station. We do this by using map(), reason why we change from dataframe into RDD, combineByKey() along corresponding codes.

Aggregation with pair RDDs

In [ ]:
rdd = RDD.map(lambda row: (row['station'], row['Present_Tmin']))
In [ ]:
combiner_method = rdd.combineByKey(
                  lambda value: (value, 1), # create combiner
                  lambda x, value: (x[0] + value, x[1] + 1), # merge value
                  lambda x, y: (x[0] + y[0], x[1] + y[1])) # merge combiner
In [ ]:
# x[0]first element / x[1]second element to get the average
avg_ptmin = combiner_method.mapValues(lambda x: x[0] / x[1])
In [ ]:
results1 = avg_ptmin.collect()
In [ ]:
for result in results1:
    print(result)

3.3 Inner Join¶

Creating dummy dataframes df2 and df3. As a good practice, we will try to specify joins based on columns. We can perform joins like min.join(max) and it will inner join (PySpark default) Present_Tmin and Present_Tmax columns. Since we might be working with big data, we might want to specify the joins with columns or any other condition.

min = new_df2.filter(new_df2['Present_Tmin'] < 25) # rows less than 25
max = new_df3.filter(new_df3['Present_Tmax'] > 26) # rows greater than 26

3.8 Anti Join (Left-anti-Join)¶

# returns data that doesn't have a match on the right side table
# Only the columns on the left side table would be included in the result. 
# Just the data filtered for the NOT IN condition
